@zcbenz I am on 10.10.5 and as mentioned before already, I start to see this error starting with electron 0.31.0 and 0.31.1. I tried today again many hours to find a reproducible scenario, but failed. I can make this error show up as soon as I cp.fork() a JS file from within a VS Code renderer window with the following code:

``` javascript
var foo = typeof console;

process.on("message", function() {

});
```

Produces:

Error: UnknownSystemError: Unknown system error, uv_pipe_open

Somehow it is already sufficient to access the console property and my forked process blows up. I can not make this happen from a bare electron app though.

Interestingly, I still see this error when my code on the renderer side is as simple as this:

``` html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
    <head>
        <meta charset="utf-8" />
        <title>Visual Studio Code</title>

        <!-- Helpers -->
        <script type="text/javascript">
            var cp = require('child_process');

            var res = cp.fork('/path to JS file');
            res.on('exit', function() {
                console.log('exit')
            })
        </script>
    </head>
    <body>
    </body>
</html>
```

This makes me wonder if anything on the main side could possibly have an impact on this issue. Any pointers as to what could that be would be appreciated.

Ok I think I got something to reproduce with a bare electron app. The tricky part was to understand that the issue reproduces when you run electron from the command line and not by dragging the app into the electron default window.

**main.js**

``` javascript
var app = require('app');  // Module to control application life.
var BrowserWindow = require('browser-window');  // Module to create native browser window.
var cp = require('child_process');

// Report crashes to our server.
require('crash-reporter').start();

// Keep a global reference of the window object, if you don't, the window will
// be closed automatically when the javascript object is GCed.
var amainWindow = null;

// Quit when all windows are closed.
app.on('window-all-closed', function() {
  if (process.platform != 'darwin')
    app.quit();
});

// This method will be called when Eolectron has done everything
// initialization and ready for creating browser windows.
app.on('ready', function() {

  function spawnSomething(cb) {
      var child = cp.spawn(process.env.SHELL, ['-ilc', 'env']);

      child.on('close', function (code, signal) {
          cb();
      });
  }

  spawnSomething(function() {

    // Create the browser window.
    mainWindow = new BrowserWindow({width: 800, height: 600, show: true});

    // and load the index.html of the app.
    mainWindow.loadUrl('file://' + __dirname + '/index.html');

    // Open the devtools.
    mainWindow.openDevTools();

    // Emitted when the window is closed.
    mainWindow.on('closed', function() {
      // Dereference the window object, usually you would store windows
      // in an array if your app supports multi windows, this is the time
      // when you should delete the corresponding element.
      mainWindow = null;
    });
  });
});
```

**index.html**

``` html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
    <head>
        <meta charset="utf-8" />

        <!-- Helpers -->
        <script type="text/javascript">
            var cp = require('child_process');

            var res = cp.fork(__dirname + '/script.js');
            res.on('exit', function() {
                console.log('exit')
            })
        </script>
    </head>
    <body class="monaco-shell vs-dark">
    </body>
</html>
```

**script.js**

``` javascript
var foo = typeof console; // commentt his line to not have the forked process exit

process.on("message", function() {

});
```

Download electron 0.31.1 for Mac and run from command line:

.../Electron.app/Contents/MacOS/Electron ./atom-app

You will see "exit" printed immediately, although the forked app should not exit. Comment out the line with the "...typeof console" and you will not get the "exit" printed and everything works fine.

I see these issues only on Mac btw, not Windows or Linux. Somehow the spawn from the main side causes issues for the fork from the renderer side?

@zcbenz Here is very simple code that causes the error. I'm justing calling require('chalk') in renderer process. That was enough to reproduce the issue.

When you open the child window by clicking on the button in the main window, you would notice the error in the console logs.

with just 1 renderer process - issue doesn't occur
with 2 renderer processes - issue occurs.

However, if you remove all the console logs messages from main.js, then this error disappears. Looks like its definitely something to do with process.stdout(). Hope this helps..

**main.js**

``` javascript
var app = require('app'),
    ipc = require('ipc'),
    BrowserWindow = require('browser-window');

var mainWindow = null;
    childWindow = null;

app.on('window-all-closed', function() {
    if (process.platform != 'darwin') {
        app.quit();
    }
});

app.on('ready', function() {
    mainWindow = new BrowserWindow({
        width: 480,
        height: 640,
    });
    mainWindow.loadUrl('file://' + __dirname + '/main.html');

    mainWindow.on('closed', function() {
        mainWindow = null;
    });

    ipc.on('child:open', function(event) {
        console.log('main.js :: ipc msg child:open received');
        openChildWindow();
    });

    openChildWindow = function() {
        if (!!childWindow) {
            console.log('main.js :: child window already open');
            childWindow.focus();
        } else {
            console.log('main.js :: create a new child window');
            childWindow = new BrowserWindow({
                width: 1080,
                height: 640,
            });
            childWindow.loadUrl('file://' + __dirname + '/child.html');

            childWindow.webContents.on('dom-ready', function() {
                console.log('main.js :: new child window loaded.');
                childWindow.show();
            });

            childWindow.on('closed', function() {
                console.log('main.js :: child window closed');
                childWindow = null;
            });
        }
    };
});
```

**main.html**

``` html
<html>
<head>
    <title>Main window</title>
</head>
<body>
    <p>
    Sample text
    </p>
    <button onClick="openChild()"> open child window </button>

    <script>
        var ipc = require('ipc');
        var chalk = require('chalk');

        function openChild() {
            console.log('main :: open child button clicked. sending child:open ipc msg to main process');
            ipc.send('child:open');
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

**child.html**

``` html
